(139, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-elena', 'Property For Sale in Elena, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'elena property for sale, buy properties in elena', 'Property For Sale in Elena Municipality of Veliko Tarnovo - Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in Elena Municipality - Veliko Tarnovo Region of Bulgaria', '<p>The tranquil municipality town of Elena is renowned for its clean air and architecture from the revival period .</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\"><br /> It is also known as \"Bethlehem of Bulgaria\" because of the number of temple like churches in the town. There are many stories of how <strong>Elena</strong> got its name one legend being, it came from when the old church \"St. Nicholas\" was consecrated on the feast of Saint King Constantine and Queen Helena and so the town was named after Queen Helena.<br/><br/>Villages in the municipality of <strong>Elena</strong>; Aplatsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-badevtsi/page-1\">Badevtsi</a>, Baevtsi, Bagalevtsi, Bajdari, Balutsi, Bebrovo, Berkovtsi, Beykovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-blaskovtsi/page-1\">Blaskovtsi</a>, Bogdansko, Bosevtsi, Boykovtsi, Brezovo, Bruchkovtsi, Buynovtsi, Byalkovtsi, Chakali, Chavdartsi, Cherni dyal, Chervenkovtsi, Daveri, Daynovtsi, Debeli rut, Dobrevtsi, Dolni Maryan, Dolni Tanchevtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-donkovtsi/page-1\">Donkovtsi</a>, Draganoskovtsi, Draganovtsi, Dragiytsi, Dragnevtsi, Drenta, Dukovtsi, Durlevtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-elena-town/page-1\">Elena Town\"</a>, Gabraka, Ganev dol, Gardevtsi, Glogovets, Golemani, Gorni kray, Gorni Tanchevtsi, Gorska, Gramatitsi, Harvalovtsi, Hristovtsi, Hunevtsi, Ignatovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-ilakov-rat/page-1\">Ilakov rat</a>, Iliyuvtsi, Ivanivanovtsi, Kamenari, Kantari, Karaivantsi, Karandili, Kirevtsi, Kojlyuvtsi, Kolari, Konstantin, Kosevtsi, Kostel, Kotutsi, Kozya reka, Krilyuvtsi, Krumchevtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-lazartsi/page-1\">Lazartsi</a>, Lesiche, Mahalnitsi, Marafeltsi, Marinovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-maryan/page-1\">Maryan</a>, Maysko, Minevtsi, Mirchovtsi, Miykovtsi, Murtvinata, Nedyalkovtsi, Neshevtsi, Nichovtsi, Nikolchovtsi, Nikolovtsi, Nyushkovtsi, Palitsi, Papratliva, Petkovtsi, Peykovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-poprusevtsi/page-1\">Poprusevtsi</a>, Popska, Radovtsi, Ralinovtsi, Raynovtsi, Rayuvtsi, Rayuvtsi, Rebrevtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-ruhovtsi/page-1\">Ruhovtsi</a>, Sabkovtsi, Shiliveri, Shilkovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-shubetsi/page-1\">Shubetsi</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-sredni-kolibi/page-1\">Sredni kolibi</a>, Stoyanovtsi, Stoychevtsi, Sultani, Svetoslavtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-tarkasheni/page-1\">Tarkasheni</a>, Titevtsi, Todyuvtsi, Tombeto, Topuzi, Trunkovtsi, Tsveklyuvtsi, Tumbevtsi, Tunki rut, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-ugoryalkovtsi/page-1\">Ugoryalkovtsi</a>, Valeto, Varzilkovtsi, Velkovtsi, Velyuvtsi, Veselina, Visokovtsi, Vulchovtsi, Vulchovtsi (hamlet), <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-yakovtsi/page-1\">Yakovtsi</a>, Zelenik<br/><span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Elena</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Elena Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"> It is situated in the <strong>Elena Balkan</strong>, part of the Central Balkan Mountain range 300 metres above sea level and the is relatively sheltered being located in the valley of the river <strong>Elena</strong> and the lush scenery is a pleasure to the eye in Spring when all the deciduous trees and fruit trees spring to life after the Winter in an abundance of different colored blossom and green buds. A substantial number of small rivers and brooks set in deep gorges and oak lined valleys are all located around <strong>Elena</strong>. The area is very popular with city dwellers and many 2nd homes are located here since the quality of the air is famed for city smog related asthma and other breathing disorders. The forests around <strong>Elena</strong> are home to indigenous deer, wolves, wild boars, foxes and hares. One can find mountain barbell and chub in the clean water of the small rivers. <strong>Elena</strong> has managed to preserve the vast majority of Bulgarian revival architectural heritage, which is evident when you walk the streets. Eight marked ecological pathways start between <strong>Elena</strong> to the neighboring village of Miykovtsi and allow visitors to enjoy the stunning <strong>Elena Balkan</strong>. <br /><br /> From archaeological discoveries, the <strong>Elena</strong> valley area has been inhabited since the late Neolithic period (4000 BC). Thracians, Romans and the Early Byzantines have settled and developed this region through the course of history. <strong>Elena</strong> developed as a settlement towards the end of the 14th Century when the capital Tarnovo was conquered by the Ottomans in 1393. The Tarnovo boyars, (noble men) and leaders settled permanently in the <strong>Elena region</strong> because their feudal possessions were hidden here away from the invading Ottomans. During the Ottoman Occupation of Bulgaria (1393 &ndash; 1878) <strong>Elena</strong> was gradually establishing itself as a commercial, cultural, administrative and vocational centre. The basic occupation and means of making a living of the local residents was agriculture, stock-breeding and crafts. From the late 18th Century <strong>Elena</strong> began her transformation (often referred to as the Golden Age) from a basic administrative town to a blooming community which weaved thick wool rugs, painted, and became a \"centre of expertise\" for these and other crafts. The prosperity of <strong>Elena</strong> in the beginning of the 19th century was also grounds for development of the cultural and education processes. <br /><br /> <strong>Not to miss in Elena</strong><br /> The Museum of Paleontology is housed in Popnikolova House. It is one of the oldest buildings in <strong>Elena</strong> and typifies the local style of architecture from the period of the Bulgarian National Revival (18th-19th centuries). Like many properties in <strong>Elena</strong>, it\'s a site of architectural and construction cultural heritage of national importance. <strong>Elena</strong> is an architectural hotspot in Bulgaria for various vernacular Bulgarian architectural styles evident in the towns\' rich and enviable selection of buildings, both public and private. There are nearly 200 buildings and monuments of culture and of these 7 are of national significance. Amongst these buildings which are symbolic for the <strong>town of Elena</strong> is the Ilarion Makariopolski museum house. It is the oldest of the maintained houses and was constructed between 1710 to 1715, located in the centre of <strong>Elena</strong>. The house has traditional overhanging eaves built out of solid oak and epitomises Bulgarian culture. The property is now part of the Museum of Revival and the tormentous Bulgarian Liberation. Two themed exhibitions are placed in it; the customs and culture of <strong>Elena</strong> during the Revival period and Christian art. <br /><br /> Another stunning example of the simple yet strong architectural form of the revival are the Five Houses of Razsukanov, located in &ldquo;Sava Katrafilov&rdquo; Street, built by the businessman Harzhi Dimitar Razsukanov at the end of the 18th century. Each terraced house has its own architectural style which differentiates it from its neighbour, however the elevation of each property has an affinity with its neighbour, the result is a perfectly balanced conglomerate of architectural style, again not to be missed. <br /><br /> Another fascinating building in <strong>Elena</strong> is the school of the Daskalolivnitsa &ndash; the first formal school in Bulgaria. The building is two stories high and is built from solid stone and oak. The ground floor has three big and unusually well lit basement rooms which were used as workshops. On the second floor the formal classrooms are located with a teacher`s room where teachers improved their teaching skills. The resultant educated teachers and intellectuals were sent to 61 towns and 31 villages throughout Bulgaria. The founder of the first Bulgarian school was Ivan Nikolov Momchilov (1819 &ndash; 1869). He was a prominent scholar and teacher of the National Revival and writer of many books, including \"Grammar of the contemporary Bulgarian language\". On the plot is also situated the Christian church &ldquo;St. Nikola&rdquo; &ndash; the oldest church in <strong>Elena</strong> and in the region, it dates back from 1518 and inside there are beautiful icons and wall-paintings. <br /> All three of the above properties are classified as cultural monuments of national importance. <br /><br /> <strong>Alternative spellings of Elena: Elayna, Eleyna, Helena, Елена</strong><br /><br /> Nearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo &ndash; 40km, Gorna Oryahovitsa &ndash; 37km, Sliven - 72km<br /> Nearest Villages: Yakovtsi - 5km Ruhovtsi - 7km<br /> Area size of town 62.42km2<br /> Altitude 293m above sea level<br /> Post code for <strong>Elena</strong> Town - 5070<br /> Latitude 42.560N Longitude 25.530E<br /> <span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Elena</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Elena - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-elena/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(140, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-dryanovo', 'Property For Sale in Dryanovo, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'dryanovo property for sale, buy properties in dryanovo', 'Property For Sale in Dryanovo Municipality of Gabrovo - Bulgaria', 'Latest property for sale in Dryanovo - Gabrovo District of Bulgaria', '<p>Dryanovo Town is the administrative centre of Dryanovo Municipality located in  North Central Bulgaria</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\"><strong>Dryanovo</strong> is known locally as the \"town of centenarians\" thanks to the healthy climatic conditions which avail here and prolong people`s life.<br/><br/><strong>Towns and villages in the municipality are:</strong> Balalaika, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-balvantsite/page-1\">Balvantsite</a>, Banari, Bilkini, Buchukovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-ganchovets/page-1\">Ganchovets</a>, Genya, Gesha, Glushka, Gozdeyka, Golemi Bulgareni, Gorni Vurpishta, Gorni Dragoycha, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-gostilitsa/page-1\">Gostilitsa</a>, Gurnya, Denchevtsi, Djurovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-dlagnya/page-1\">Dlugnya</a>, Dobrenite, Dolni Vurpishta, Dolni Dragoycha, Docha, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-dryanovo-town/page-1\">Dryanovo Town</a>, Durcha, Elentsite, Zaya, Ignatovtsi, Iskra, Kalomen, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-karaivantsa/page-1\">Karaivantsa</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-katrandzhii/page-1\">Katrandjii</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-kereka/page-1\">Kereka</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-kosarka/page-1\">Kosarka</a>, Kosilka, Krancha, Kuklya, Kumanite, Kartipanya, Malki Bulgareni, Manoya, Mutsya, Neychovtsi, Peyna, Petkovtsi, Plachka, Parsha, Radancheto, Radovtsi, Ritya, Runya, Rusinovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-salasuka/page-1\">Salasuka</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-skalsko/page-1\">Skalsko</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-slaveykovo/page-1\">Slaveykovo</a>, Sokolovo, Stancha, Suholoevtsi, Syarovtsi, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-turkincha/page-1\">Turkincha</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-tsareva-livada/page-1\">Tsareva Livada</a>, Chukovo, Shushnya, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-yantra/page-1\">Yantra</a><br /><span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Dryanovo</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Dryanovo Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"> The municipality town of <strong>Dryanovo</strong>, in the district of Gabrovo, is situated to the north of the Central-Balkan Mountains, and the foothills are called the <strong>Dryanovo</strong> Balkan. The town is situated along both banks of the river <strong>Dryanovo</strong> which is a tributary of the Yantra River. <br /><br /> The town centre is situated just off the main Ruse-Veliko Tarnovo-Gabrovo-Kazanlak-Stara Zagora highway and also benefits from being on the railway line which is on the North to the South rail corridor. <br /><br /> <strong>Dryanovo</strong> developed rapidly during the time of the Bulgarian Renaissance and in 1883 it was declared a town. Craftsmen including masons and woodcarvers made <strong>Dryanovo</strong> a countrywide known town and even internationally, as far away as the Turkish Empire. Close to <strong>Dryanovo</strong> at the Bacho Kiro cave an amazing discovery was made, human skeleton remains from the Paleolithic period were discovered. Furthermore in the surrounding villages many relics of Thracian and Roman villages, fortresses, columns with finials and inscriptions and tools and ornaments (Boruna and Diskoduratera fortresses) have been discovered. <br /><br /> <strong>Places to visit in Dryanovo</strong><br /><br /> <strong>Dryanovo</strong> is famed for its beautiful monastery which originally was located 2 km. north of the current monastery and was built by the noble brothers Assen and Peter. In the 14th century the monastery was one of the main centre&rsquo;s of Hesychasm which interpreted means stillness, rest, quiet and silence and sheltered many monks. At the beginning of the 15th century, the monastery was destroyed by the Ottoman Empire soldiers like so many others.<br /><br /> It was later rebuilt in its current location, however once again the Ottomans struck and it was raised to the ground. It wasn\'t until the end of the 17th Century that it was rebuilt for the 3rd time and these structures can still be seen to this day, the only remaining part of the old church was the nave which was half built into the ground and can also still be seen next to the present church. Further renovation of the monastery began during the time Abbot Raphael was the head of the local church and during 40 years of the 19th century residential and teaching buildings were constructed along with the new church. By the end of the 19th Century <strong>Dryanovo</strong> Monastery had become the largest and best-developed of all the monasteries in the Veliko Tarnovo region.<br /><br /> <strong>Dryanovo</strong> monks proactively supported the revolutionaries struggle for liberation from the Turkish occupation. The monastery was one of the main headquarters of the Bulgarian revolutionaries and Vasil Levski and Georgi Izmirliev often hid there whilst planning their campaign.<br /><br />There was a large cache of weapons, ammunition and food, which is why during the April Uprising detachment of Father Hariton and Bacho Kiro engaged in battle against the Ottomans and whilst Bacho Kiro escaped, he later got betrayed and captured and finally hung in Veliko Tarnovo.<br /><br /> The Bacho Kiro cave was named in his honour and is on the eco trail and well worth a visit as is this beautiful historical area. This battle destroyed just about all the buildings and structures of the monastery save the church just after the Liberation. So a new wing was built and a museum and in 1925 the bell tower was erected. <br /><br /> Nowadays you can walk around this beautiful landscape and stay in the monastery in cozy rooms with 2 or 3 beds, in the monastery grounds are a couple of good restaurants serving authentic rural Bulgarian cuisine, the \"Andaka\" Tavern and the \"<strong>Dryanovo</strong> Monastery\" Complex Restaurant and in <strong>Dryanovo</strong> there are also a number of restaurants. <br /><br /> Whilst in <strong>Dryanovo town</strong> take a look at the Lafchieva kushta (Lafchieva House) designed and built by Kolyu Gaidardjiyata, who was a master-builder from <strong>Dryanovo</strong>. It was built in 1840 and is also well known as \"the house without nails\". Perhaps the most famous master builder and architect was born in <strong>Dryanovo</strong> in 1800.<br /><br />Kolyo Ficheto was orphaned in <strong>Dryanovo</strong> at the age of 3 years and at 10 years old began studying with Tryavna master builders. When reaching the age of 17 he studied with masters from the ancient city of Korca (now Albania) how to cut and dress stone, afterwards he studied intently the construction of churches, bell towers and bridges of Bratsigovo in the Rhodope Mountains of Bulgaria. His works include the Ikonomova kushta (Ikonomova House) in Dryanovo which is one of two houses, the other being the house with the monkey in Tarnovo; it was built in 1859 for a priest named Vasil Ikonomov.<br /><br />The hall of this property has a finely detailed hand wood-carved ceiling emulating the sun &ndash; which was the favourite motif during renaissance the period. Many more bridges, churches and clock towers can be seen around the Veliko Tarnovo region built by Kolyo Ficheto. There is also the Kolyo Ficheto museum next to the House without nails which is certainly worth having a look around to learn more about his abilities as a Master Builder and the Revival architectural and craftwork movement. <br /><br /> <strong>Alternative spellings of Dryanovo:</strong> Dryanavo, Drianovo, Dreanavo, Dreanovo, Drianavo, Дряново<br /><br /> Nearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo &ndash; 24km, Gabrovo &ndash; 20km, Tryavna - 17km<br /> Nearest Villages: Ganchovets - 4km Zaya - 4km<br /> Area size of town 28.096km2<br /> Altitude 200 - 299m above sea level<br /> Post code for <strong>Dryanovo</strong> Town - 5370<br /> Latitude 42.983N Longitude 25.492E<br /> <span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Dryanovo</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Dryanovo - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-dryanovo/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(141, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-gabrovo-town', 'Property For Sale in the Municipality of Gabrovo, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'gabrovo property for sale, buy properties in gabrovo town', 'Property For Sale in the municipality of Gabrovo - Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in Gabrovo Municipality - North Central Bulgaria', '<p>Gabrovo is situated almost in the geographic centre of Bulgaria and is famous for it\'s unique humour and satire.</p>\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\"><br /> To be born a \"Gabrovian\" is a privilege since the townsfolk are money savers and love to haggle at a market since \"tightness\" runs in their veins; they know how to get water out of stone - an invaluable lesson taught by their predecessors! <span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Gabrovo</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Gabrovo Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"><strong>Gabrovo</strong> is located on the River Yantra and stretches along both banks for several kilometers. <br /><br /> <strong>Villages in the municipality are:</strong> Angelov, Armenite, Baevtsi, Balanite, Balinovtsi, Bankovtsi, Bekriite, Belomajite, Bobevtsi, Bogdanchovtsi, Bojentsi, Boynovtsi, Boycheta, Boltata, Boriki, Borskoto, Brunetsite, Byalkovo, Chavei, Charkovo, Chervena lokva, Chernevtsi, Chitakovtsi, Chukilite, Debel dyal, Djumriite, Divetsi, Donino, Draganovtsi, Draganchetata, Dragievtsi, Dragomani, Dumnitsi, Ezeroto, Furgovtsi, Gaykini, Gaytanite, Garvan, Genovtsi, Genchovtsi, Gergini, Gledatsi, Gornova mogila, Grablevtsi, Gubene, Haracherite, Ivanili, Ivankovtsi, Iglika, Iztochnik, Jivko, Jultesh, Kalchovtsi, Kameshtitsa, Karali, Kievtsi, Kmetovtsi, Kmetcheta, Kozi rog, Kolishovtsi, Kopcheliite, Kostadinite, Kostenkovtsi, Lesicharka, Loza, Malini, Malusha, Mejdeni, Mechkovitsa, Milkovtsi, Mihaylovtsi, Michkovtsi, Morovetsite, Mrahori, Muzga, Nikolchovtsi, Novakovtsi, Ovoshtartsi, Orlovtsi, Parchovtsi, Peyovtsi, Penkovtsi, Petrovtsi, Petsovtsi, Popari, Popovtsi, Potok, Prahali, Prodanovtsi, Partevtsi, Raynovtsi, Rahovtsi, Rachevtsi, Redeshkovtsi, Ruychovtsi, Ryazkovtsi, Svinarski dol, Sedyankovtsi, Seykovtsi, Semerdjiite, Smilovtsi, Solari, Spantsi, Spasovtsi, Starilkovtsi, Stefanovo, Stoevtsi, Stoykovtsi, Stoychovtsi, Stomanetsite, Subotkovtsi, Sharani, Shipchenite, Todorovtsi, Todorcheta, Torbalajite, Trapeskovtsi, Trunito,  Tsvyatkovtsi, Uzunite, Velkovtsi, Vetrovo, Vlaychovtsi, Vlahovtsi, Vrabtsite, Vranilovtsi, Vulkov dol, Yavorets, Yankovtsi, Yasenite, Zdravkovets, Zeleno darvo, Zlatevtsi, Ski resort Uzana, Area of Etara, Area of Lyulyacite<br /><br /> <strong>Gabrovo</strong> and its surrounding area has been inhabited since Neolithic times and gained economic stature after Veliko Tarnovo became the capital in the 12th century. Craftsmanship and trade brought properity to the town in part due proximity to both the capital and the Balkan mountain passes since it was a small pass village with around a hundred properties during medieval times. Legend has it that <strong>Gabrovo</strong> was founded by a blacksmith called Racho, whose furnace was close to a hornbeam tree, габър, (gabar) in Bulgarian, so the village acquired its name. It turned from a village into a small town developing into a cultural and spriritual centre during the Ottoman ruling as many escapees from Tarnovo fled there, thanks mainly to its poor access. <br /><br /> The Bulgarian Orthodox rite of the priests throwing a wooden cross in a river and believers jumping into the icy waters to \"save\" the cross developed in <strong>Gabrovo</strong> in the River Yantra. <br /><br /> After the Liberation of Bulgaria in 1878, <strong>Gabrovo</strong> developed as a centre of industry on the basis of its economic and craft history. Limited companies developed, factories were built and connections to large stock exchanges developed, indeed it was even cited by some entrepreneurs as the \"Bulgarian Manchester\". Consequent to this mass development and its requirement for water <strong>Gabrovo</strong> became the longest city in Bulgaria, post-World War 2 industry all but killed off the Yantra River, but since heavy industry has all but gone, the river and surrounding valley has cleaned up. <br /><br /> Now due to its clean mountain air, historical and ethnographical complexes <strong>Gabrovo</strong> has become a popular tourist centre. The Municipality of <strong>Gabrovo</strong> and the adjoining countryside is considered by many as the most ecologically clean region in Bulgaria. The diverse and abundant flora and fauna proves this whether walking the the Central Balkan National Park above the town where where you can take binoculars and a camera to shoot trophies such as bear, red deer and mouflon, mouflon is thought to be one of two original ancestors of all modern day sheep originating on the islands of Corsica, Sardina, and Cyprus, but now successfully introduced in Central Bulgaria. The mouflon lives in terrain around Uzana above the tree line and in the delightful mountain meadows. Specific interests are catered for specialising in local culture and history, photography, caving and pot-holing, alpine cross skiing experience and hunting. <br /><br /> <strong>What to do in Gabrovo</strong><br /> A definite must do is visit the picturesque village Etar which is an architectural and working ethnographical complex and is unique in as much that all the crafts and trades are exhibited in a working condition. Watch steel being ground and shaped into knives, wood being turned into bowls, kitchenware and spindles, leather craft, a bakery and a washing place. However what is more fascinating is that all these crafts are powered by water which is channeled from the hill down sluices to each working exhibit. After watching please support the craftsmen and women by purchasing their wears and delicious food. <br /><br /> In the town of <strong>Gabrovo</strong> is the House of Humour and Satire which is one of the 100 national tourist sites of Bulgaria it is renowned for its high quality of tourst services offered and the access to and around the museum for disabled customers and it is possible to buy some <strong>Gabrovo</strong> humour from the souvenir shop. This is the only Bulgarian shop where you can find unique <strong>Gabrovo</strong> artefacts such as 1/2 a coffee-cup, clocks that work counter-clockwise, cups for reading one\'s future, cups for moustached men and the list goes on....Buy the latest publication of <strong>Gabrovo</strong> Humour specifically focusing on <strong>Gabrovo</strong> townsfolk habits about not spending money its available in 5 languages or try the kitchen apron with famous <strong>Gabrovo</strong> recipes to survive an economic crisis, how very apt! <br /><br /> Hiking around the Central Balkan National Park is assisted by clearly marked routes which also include 10 equestrian trails and 4 extreme mountain bike trails, as well as thematic fauna and flora routes for bird, plant, and large mammal spotting. There is a total of 20 holiday chalets with a combined capacity of over 1,400 beds in the territory of the park, all operated by the Bulgarian Tourism Board. Furthermore private enterprise operates 264 beds, and three tourist lodges with 40 beds the latter offering very basic accommodation but are a Godsend when getting caught out in inclement weather. <br /><br /> Most visitors have heard of Bansko, Borovets and Pamporovo however, beneath the peak of Ispolin, in the heart of the Stara Planina mountain and only 20km from <strong>Gabrovo</strong>, 1249m above sea level, is located the &ldquo;Uzana&rdquo; - Bulgaria\'s geographical centre. It is the epitome of clean and beautiful Bulgaria with crystal clear water, fresh unpolluted air, stunning nature and serenity. In the winter Uzana is a great location for mountain sports and yet its kept quiet, for beginners and children there are several short and easy runs with mini-drags and ski-schools, and for experienced skiers there is a 1,200 m long piste with a ski-drug. For visitors who just want to take in the scenery and stunning natural beauty why not take the effortless horse drawn sleigh? <br /><br /> <strong>Alternative spellings of <strong>Gabrovo</strong>: Gabravo, Габрово</strong><br /><br /> Nearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo &ndash; 45km, Dryanovo &ndash; 20km, Tryavna - 22km<br /> Nearest Villages: Prodanovtsi - 4km, Ryaskovtzi - 5km<br /> Area size of Town of <strong>Gabrovo</strong>: 233.817km2<br /> Latitude: 42.87622N Longitude: 25.31816E<br /> Altitude: 300 - 499m above sea level<br /> Post code of Town of <strong>Gabrovo</strong>: 5300<br /> <span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Gabrovo</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Gabrovo - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-gabrovo-town/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(142, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-sevlievo', 'Property For Sale in Sevlievo, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'sevlievo property for sale, buy properties in sevlievo', 'Property For Sale in the Municipality of Sevlievo in North Central Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in Sevlievo Municipality - North Central Bulgaria', '<p>The very latest property for sale in the municipality of Sevlievo - Gabrovo region of North Bulgaria.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\">Sevlievo is positioned in a sheltered valley on the banks of the River Rositsa. It has a microclimate which tends to keep it milder in winter than the surrounding hilly countryside and hot in Summer. <span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Sevlievo</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Sevlievo Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\">The earliest traces of settlements in this region date back to around 8000 BC and a few Thracian tombs have been discovered.<br /><br /> <strong>Villages in the municipality of  Sevlievo: </strong> Agatovo, Baeva livada, Batoshevo, Berievo, Boazat, Bogatovo, Burya, Bulgari, Damyanovo, Debeltsovo, Dismanitsa, Dobromirka, Dryanat, Dushevo, Dushevski kolibi, Dyalak,  Enev rat, Gorna Rositsa,  Gradishte,  Gradnitsa, Hirevo, Idilevo, Karamichevtsi, Kastel, Koriata, Kormyansko, Kramolin, Krushevo, Kravenik, Kupen, Lovnidol, Malinovo, Malki Vurshets, Marinovtsi, Mladen, Mlechevo, Petko Slaveykov, Popska, Rogulyat, Ryahovtsite, Selishte, Sennik, Shopite, Shumata, Stokite, Stolut, Tabashka,Tumbalovo, Tarhovo, Ugorelets, Valevtsi, Voynishka<br /><br /> The settlement developed during the 15th century as a small village producing timber products including boards for building. Before this it was an administrative, military, and economic settlement between the 10th -12th centuries but exact historical facts are hard to come since the medieval  fortress and settlement of Hotalich was situated 4 km northwest of current <strong>Sevlievo</strong> and it was located here primarily for its strategic importance. Hotalich appeared in the gorge of Rositsa River in the 5th century and Byzantines were responsible for the fort\'s erection. It protected the country from barbaric assaults from the north and the fort was a massive fortification with Tarnovo, Pliska and Preslav being bigger! <br /><br /> Only in 1979 was the fort discovered beneath the ground by mistake and archaeologists discovered a church and an older temple dating back to the 5th century. They have also discovered many stone buildings beneath the soil, uncovering a tower and two fortified massive walls one of which dates back to the early Byzantine period and the second from the 9th to the 10th Centuries. <br /><br /> During the early 17th Century it was mentioned as \"Selvi\" or \"Servi\" where its current name originated from and originated from the vegetation which grew locally in the surrounding land. The settlement developed thanks to its silkworm breeding industry and the silk-trade brought wealth to the town since a large demand grew for silk as far afield as Austria, France, and Romania. <br /><br /> <strong>Sevlievo</strong> was completely devastated by fire started by the Kurdzhalii (Turkish brigades) in 1798. Afterwards the village developed into a small town being rebuilt and in 1834 the church of St Prophet Eliah was restored and in 1836 the Batoshevo Monastery was rebuilt after the fires. <br /><br /> The population of <strong>Sevlievo</strong> was to endure another disaster as the great plague in 1838 took its toll of the townsfolk! In 1844, Hadzhi Stoyan Nikolov had a large school built at his own expense and Kolyu Ficheto, the acclaimed master builder of the Bulgarian National Revival period, built the old stone bridge over the river Rositsa during the 1850\'s. In 1870, Vasil Levski master planned and managed a revolutionary committee which prepared the townsfolk of <strong>Sevlievo</strong> for the April uprising in 1876. The occupation of the Ottomans ended on the 2nd July 1877 and since this date <strong>Sevlievo</strong> has grown into a wealthy municipality town, thanks to companies such as American Standard investing millions into one of the biggest factories producing bathroom fixtures and fittings, marketed under such brands as Ideal Standard and Armitage Shanks. <br /><br /> <strong>What to do in <strong>Sevlievo</strong>?</strong><br /><br /> The Monument of Freedom is unavoidable in the centre of <strong>Sevlievo</strong> and was constructed in 1894. Designed by Otto Horeishi from Austria, who was an artist and sculptor admired by Prince Ferdinand, who in 1908 was crowned as Tsar of Bulgaria after arriving into Bulgaria in 1887, and Arnoldo Zocchi a talented Italian sculptor of the late 19th and early 20th century being born in Florence, the city of so many famous Italian artists, sculptors and master builders and died in 1940 in Rome. The base pillar and foundation stone of the monument is an original stone column from the Roman town of Nikopolis ad Istrum north of Veliko Tarnovo and the figure crowning the column was carved in Vienna. So when you take a photo and admire this work, consider the centuries of history that is actually enshrined in this monument including the Bulgarians who died in the April Uprising and the Russo-Turkish War and the 8 local resistance fighters from <strong>Sevlievo</strong> were hanged at this very location. <br /><br /> The Town Museum of History is located in the building of the first secular school, named Hadzhistoyanovo School out of respect to Hadzhi Stoyan Nikolov who paid for its construction and again can be found in the centre of the town at 6, Petko R Slaveykov Street. The street name derives itself from Petko Rachov Slaveykov who was teaching for a short while at the school and who was a famous poet, publicist and folklorist. Sevlievo&rsquo;s current history museum opened its doors in 1954 and its exhibits have increased to 45 000 plus items. The museum has exhibits from the Stone Age to the present time discovered in the immediate surroundings. The collection of exhibits and artifacts follow in a chronological manner in 4 properties. The Hadzhistoyanovo School houses some unique ancient artifacts from the Thracian and Roman periods. Many items were found during excavation works at the ancient settlement of Hotalich. The collection includes unique jewelry and there is also a renaissance period collection. It displays some of the most developed craftwork from the <strong>Sevlievo</strong> region during the late 18th and 19th centuries along with the associated languish of the Liberation struggles, exhibits of weapons used during the liberation and from 1876, the seal of the <strong>Sevlievo</strong> revolutionary committee, prior to the liberation in 1877. There are also other historical exhibits which demonstrate the way people lived during these times and house layouts, furniture and utensils and tools. <br /><br /> Tabahanata House is a restored leather and tanning workshop which dates back to the 1700\'s and is the only such example preserved in Bulgaria. As is often the case, the best way to see these sights is to walk around the centre where you will also come across the clock tower which was built in 1777, 18 m high, the St. Prophet Iliya Church at 12, Skobelev Street, constructed in 1834 laying claim to a beautiful wood-carved iconostasis, which is a timber ornately carved partition. The stone bridge over the river Rositsa built by the famous Kolyu Ficheto during 1857-1858 and comparable to his bridge at Byala. <br /><br /> For dirt riding enthusiats the world championship motocross heats and competitions take place at Gorna Rositsa&rsquo;s motocross, including the Bulgarian Grand Prix which is a few km\'s from <strong>Sevlievo</strong>. Also take a picnic to Hotalich where the old fortifications were discovered only just over 30 years ago, located 4 kms North West of the town. <br /><br /> <strong>Alternative spellings of Sevlievo:</strong> Sevleyavo, Sevleyevo, Sevlayvo, Sevleevo, Sevleyvo, Севлиево<br /><br /> Nearest Towns:  Gabrovo - 27km, Dryanovo &ndash; 34km, Veliko Tarnovo &ndash; 45km<br /> Nearest Villages: Krushevo - 6km,  Yavorets - 10km, Mladen &ndash; 13km<br /> Area size of Town of <strong>Sevlievo</strong>: 41.244km2<br /> Altitude: 100 - 199m above sea level<br /> Post code of Town of <strong>Sevlievo</strong>: 5400<br /> Latitude: 43.026N Longitude: 25.114E<br /> <span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Sevlievo</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Sevlievo - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-sevlievo/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(143, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-tryavna', 'Property For Sale in Tryavna, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'tryavna property for sale, buy properties in tryavna', 'Property For Sale in the Municipality of Tryavna  in North Central Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in Tryavna Municipality - North Central Bulgaria', '<p>The very latest property for sale in the municipality of Tryavna - Gabrovo region of North Bulgaria.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\">Without doubt, the centre of Tryavna situated in the Tryavna river valley is a romantic spot whose history goes back to the settlement originating from the 12th century during the reign of the Assen Dynasty. <span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Tryavna</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Tryavna Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"><strong>Villages in the municipality of Tryavna are:</strong>  Azmanite,  Armyankovtsi,  Bangeytsi,  Bahretsi,  Belitsa,  Bijovtsi,  Brejnitsite,  Burdarite,  Burdeni,  Chakalite, Chernovruh, Daevtsi,  Dimievtsi,  Dobrevtsi,  Dolni Marentsi,  Dolni Radkovtsi, Dolni Tomchevtsi,  Donkino,  Donchovtsi,  Dragnevtsi,  Drandarite,  Darvari,  Daskarite, Enchovtsi, Furevtsi,  Furtuni, Gaydari,  Genchovtsi,  Glutnitsite,  Golemi Stanchovtsi, Gorni Damyanovtsi,  Gorni Marentsi,  Gorni Radkovtsi,  Gorni Tsonevtsi,  Goryani, Hristovtsi, Ivan Dimov,  Irinetsi, Kashentsi,  Kerenite,  Kiselkovtsi,  Kisiytsite,  Koevtsi,  Koychovtsi,  Kolyu Ganev,  Konarskoto,  Kreslyuvtsi,  Krustenyatsite,  Krustets,  Malki Stanchovtsi, Malchovtsi,  Manevtsi,  Marutsekovtsi,  Mateshovtsi,  Milevtsi,  Mihovtsi,  Mogilite,  Mrazetsi,  Nedyalkovtsi,  Nenovtsi,  Nikachkovtsi,  Nikolaevo,  Nojerite,  Noseite,  Okoliite,  Oshanite,  Pavlevtsi,  Planintsi, Town of Plachkovtsi,  Pobak,  Popgergevtsi,  Popraykovtsi,  Prestoy,  Purjigrah, Radevtsi,  Radino,  Radoevtsi,  Raevtsi,  Raynushkovtsi,  Ralevtsi,  Rachovtsi,  Rashovite,  Ruevtsi,  Svirtsi,  Sechen kamak,  Skortsite,  Slivovo, Staynovtsi,  Stanchov han,  Strajata,  Stramtsi,  Todoretsite,  Tomchevtsi,  Urvata, Velentsi,  Velkovo,  Velchovtsi,  Vladovtsi,  Vlasatili,  Voynitsite,  Vulkovtsi<br/><br/>\r\nAfter the Ottoman invasion, <strong>Tryavna</strong> was a distinct settlement, whose inhabitants were prized to guard the pass through the Balkan Mountains to Edirne and Istanbul. <strong>Tryavna</strong>, whose name originates from the hardy grass species which is prolific in this area, reached prosperity by the end of the 17th Century when the wood carvers and craftsmen, artists and master builders established themselves as some of the most talented in the region. The influence of the members of the <strong>Tryavna</strong> Art School can be seen everywhere. Master builders constructed stunningly beautiful houses, schools and churches. Artists with Icon-painting ability ornamented the churches with icons and mural paintings and wood workers contributed by designing and carving magnificent ceilings, altars and windows. Felix Kanits, the traveling journalist and commentator of the time visited <strong>Tryavna</strong> in 1872 and called it the \"Bulgarian Nuremberg\". A lot of <strong>Tryavna</strong> townsfolk took part in the struggles and uprisings for an independent Bulgarian church and national awareness and liberation. <strong>Tryavna</strong> is the birthplace of Vasil Levski\'s compatriot, Angel Kunchev and Petko R. Slaveikov lived there too and his prominent son, Pencho R Slaveikov was born in <strong>Tryavna</strong> well noted for his poetry and writings. The exceptionally healthy climate and air along with the dramatic and beautiful countryside, allowed <strong>Tryavna</strong> to become a leading resort as early as the late 19th century and now many hotels and guest houses can be found here today! <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>What to do in Tryavna?</strong><br/><br/>\r\nThe unique old world environment of <strong>Tryavna</strong> is primarily due to its renaissance architecture. Generations of master-builders constructed churches, bridges, schools and the distinctive <strong>Tryavna</strong> house. The Renaissance architectural assemblages of Petko Slaveykov and Assenevtsi in the Kachunska Mahala area of <strong>Tryavna</strong> have preserved their romantic authenticity. Two-storey houses with bow-windows facing the street and wide eaves attract admirers of Bulgarian revival architecture from all over Europe and further afield. Among the masterpieces of <strong>Tryavna</strong>\'s architectural heritage are buildings built by Dimitar Sergyuv and the best way to see them is by walking around the town. In particular look for the Kalinchev house 1830, the Dobrev 1834, the Raykov 1846 and the Kirev house 1851, are amongst the most celebrated architectural results of such artistic imagination of the famous builder. <br/><br/>\r\nAlso check out the vaulted stone bridge designed and built by Dimitar Sergyuv in 1844-45 which links harmoniously the two areas of \"old\" <strong>Tryavna</strong> on either side of the babbling river. In 1814 the <strong>Tryavna</strong> clock tower was built and the local legend says in order to receive permission from the Otoman regime to build the tower, <strong>Tryavna</strong> women stopped wearing their traditional head dress, \"sokai\", which resembled a royal crown. All in all there are over 140 monuments and buildings of revival architecture in <strong>Tryavna</strong> old town and it has been declared an architectural reserve. The best examples being in Dyado Nikola Square, Slaveikov Street, Petar Bogdanov Street, Kachunska Mahala quarter. Must sees are; the Daskalov\'s House 1804 27A, Slaveikov Street in which the Museum of Woodcarving and Icon-Painting is located. The two uniquely beautiful oak-carved ceilings by Dimiter Oshanina and Ivan Bochukovetsa in 1808 which they carved after a bet made between them as to who could create the most technically intricate ceiling! The <strong>Tryavna</strong> School of Icon-Painting Museum at 1, Breza Street, contains in excess of 160 icons. The Angel Kunchev Museum-House is the home of one of the celebrated Bulgarian resistance fighters against the occupying Turkish forces. The St. Archangel Mihail Church dates back to 1819 with its magnificent ornately carved iconostasis which is a wooden partition with doors and multiple lines of icons separating the \"bema\" from the \"nave\" in Orthodox churches being the work of Vitan Koyuv-Junior. Also while there check the amazingly stunning bishop\'s throne made by Priest Koyu Vitanov in 1821. The church all has an original cross of palisander wood carved with 12 scenes from the Bible on it. <br/><br/>\r\nEvery other year on the 26th and 27th May are held Slaveikov\'s Day events which include a collection of cultural events encompassing diverse festivities and celebrations, poetry and literary readings culminating in the award of the Slaveikov Prize. <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Alternative spellings of Tryavna: </strong> Triavna, Treavna, Treeavna, Tryavnar, Triavnar, Трявна<br/><br/>\r\nNearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo – 39km, Dryanovo – 16km, Gabrovo - 22km<br/>\r\nNearest Villages: Dobrevtsi - 2km  Hristovtsi - 4km<br/>\r\nArea size of Town of <strong>Tryavna</strong>: 16.122km2<br/>\r\nAltitude: 300 - 499m above sea level<br/>\r\nPost code of Town of <strong>Tryavna</strong>: 5350<br/>\r\nLatitude: 42.867N Longitude: 25.5E<br/>\r\n\r\n\r\n<span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Tryavna</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Tryavna - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-tryavna/page-1', 'Desktop');
