(144, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-gorna-oryahovitsa', 'Property For Sale in Gorna Oryahovitsa, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'gorna oriahvitsa property for sale, buy properties in gorna oryahovitsa', 'Property For Sale in Gorna Oryahovitsa Municipality in North Central Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in the Municipality of Gorna Oryahovitsa', '<p>Gorna Oryahovitsa Town is the administrative centre of Gorna Oryahovitsa Municipality</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\"><br />Located in North Bulgaria; Gorna is somewhat over shadowed by its neighbouring ancient capital city, Veliko Tarnovo. However it is a very popular local destination for shopping and buying fresh meat and vegetables and has a bustling atmosphere with a few street cafes to ease the day.<br/><br/><strong>Within the municipality are:</strong>the town of <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-dolna-oryahovitsa/page-1\">Dolna Oryahovitsa</a> and villages of <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-draganovo/page-1\">Draganovo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-gorski-dolen-trambesh/page-1\">Gorski Dolen Trambesh</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-gorski-goren-trambesh/page-1\">Gorski Goren Trambesh</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-krusheto/page-1\">Krusheto</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-paisiy/page-1\">Paisiy</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-parvomaytsi/page-1\">Parvomaytsi</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-pisarevo/page-1\">Pisarevo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-polikraishte/page-1\">Polikraishte</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-pravda/page-1\">Pravda</a>, Strelets, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-varbitsa/page-1\">Varbitsa</a>, Yantra.<br /><span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Gorna Oryahovitsa Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"> \r\nThe 1st early settlement dates to middle Neolithic man after whom there is evidence of a Thracian settlement between the towering Kamaka Hill and the high Plateau which now has the beautiful village of Arbanasi located. The Thracians constructed the \"Kamaka Fortress\" in the 5th century BC and it continued to serve as a fortification until the 1st century BC, after which the Romans built up their own fortified settlement after destroying it in earlier battle. The Romans grew grapes and produced wine, a practice still very much in evidence today, and this increased the settlements revenues and brought with it regional economic power.  Typically after the Roman Empire diminished there is little account for the settlement during the Slav period.<br/><br/>\r\nTowards the end of the 12th century, the new mighty settlement was in full development, Tarnovgrad (Veliko Tarnovo) and there was a need to protect the incoming roads to this developing city. Many fortresses were built, Rahovets (4 km northwest of <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong>) being one and \"rah\" being Persian for road, thus the name it is now known originated from this term for road. Rahovets survived until 1444 when it was destroyed in a battle with the Ottomans after which 3 small villages developed during the first few centuries of Ottoman rule which included Golyama (Greater) Rahovitsa. <br/><br/>\r\nDuring the Bulgarian National Revival, <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> gradually turned into an ever growing and wealthy settlement. Trades and crafts prospered and every Friday there was a big market trading in cattle, fruit, vegetables and grain, timber, and charcoal for the production of steel tools and knives. Between 1822 and 1835 schools were built and opened and 1850 saw the 1st girls school opened here. <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> was formally recognised as a regional town in 1870, having nearly 5000 townsfolk, over1200 properties and 5 churches. <br/><br/>\r\nVasil Levski organised a revolutionary committee in <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> and its townsfolk joined the planning of the revolution during 1869 and he later visited the town twice more during the preparation of the April Uprising. <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> was given credibility as a centre of the First Revolutionary District with Stefan Stambolov as its Head of Staff. However, the uprising was doomed and fighters were demoralised with one leader being hung in <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> Square, allegedly shouting \"How good it is to die for the freedom of Bulgaria\" in his last breaths during 1876. Townsfolk of <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> fought with Hristo Botev and his armed volunteers during the Russo-Turkish War of Liberation when the Imperial Russian Army liberated <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> from Ottoman rule on 26 June 1877. <br/><br/>\r\nUpon <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> being liberated it developed as a significant transport centre/hub (predominantly railway) and this has developed exporting agricultural produce in modern history during the recent socialist times. Furthermore it has an airport which holds International status making Its proximity to the old ancient capital of Veliko Tarnovo, the tourist centre Arbanasi, and all the surrounding monasteries, Roman settlements and vineyards a hot tourist destination! <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>What to do in Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong><br/>\r\nIn 1962 the historical museum in <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> was established to encapture the historical heritage of the municipality. Many valuable exhibits, not only of regional interest but of National importance, are exhibited in the museum. Especially since the town was one of the centres of the April Uprising in 1876. <br/>\r\nApart from Ryahovets Fortress many archeological digs have occurred throughout the region during recent years and the findings of these excavations are a most impressive part of the exhibition of the museum. Interestingly an old photographic studio has been preserved in its authentic original style housing ancient prints and is also part of the Museum\'s exhibition. The market in <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong> is most certainly worth a visit being colourful and full of hustle and bustle. <br /><br /> <strong>Alternative spelling of Gorna Oryahovitsa:</strong> Gorna Oriahovitsa, Gorna Oryahovica, Gorna Oriahovica, Gorna Oryahovitza, Gorna Oryakhovitsa, Горна Оряховица<br /><br /> \r\n\r\nNearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo – 9km, Lyaskovets – 3km, Dolna Oryahovitsa - 6km<br/>\r\nNearest Villages: Arbanasi - 4km Parvomaytsi - 4km<br/>\r\nArea size of Town of <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong>: 21.108km2<br/>\r\nLatitude: 43.1278N Longitude: 25.7017E<br/>\r\nAltitude: 100 - 199m above sea level<br/>\r\nPost code of Town of <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong>: 5100<br/>\r\n<span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Gorna Oryahovitsa</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Gorna Oryahovitsa - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-gorna-oryahovitsa/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(145, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-pavlikeni', 'Property For Sale in Pavlikeni, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'pavlikeni property for sale, buy properties in pavlikeni', 'Property For Sale in Pavlikeni Municipality of Veliko Tarnovo - Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in Pavlikeni - Veliko Tarnovo Region of Bulgaria', '<p>Pavlikeni is the administrative centre of Pavlikeni Municipality located in North Bulgaria.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\"><br /> During Thracian and Roman times <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> was a centre for manufacturing ceramics and pottery evidenced by remains being found in the immediate vicinity. The town has natural mineral springs, this clearly was a feature which would have made this location popular with the Romans and today the Park Hotel has hot mineral spa treatments for guests and visitors on the edge of the town.<br/><br/><strong>Villages in the municipality are:</strong> Batak, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-butovo/page-1\">Butovo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-byala-cherkva/page-1\">Byala Cherkva</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-daskot/page-1\">Daskot</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-dimcha/page-1\">Dimcha</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-dolna-lipnitsa/page-1\">Dolna Lipnitsa</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-gorna-lipnitsa/page-1\">Gorna Lipnitsa</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-karaisen/page-1\">Karaisen</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-lesicheri/page-1\">Lesicheri</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-mihaltsi/page-1\">Mihaltsi</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-musina/page-1\">Musina</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-nedan/page-1\">Nedan</a>, Patresh, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-paskalevets/page-1\">Paskalevets</a>, Rositsa, Slomer, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-stambolovo/page-1\">Stambolovo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-vishovgrad/page-1\">Vishovgrad</a>, Varbovka.<br /><span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Pavlikeni</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Pavlikeni Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"> The modern town developed during the 13th and14th centuries as a village called Marinopoltsi. However most of its residents followed the Christian sect of Paulicianism and the name <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> derived from this. During the Ottoman rule of Bulgaria, the size of <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> increased dramatically since many Turks chose to settle here and made it a sole Turkish village. <br /><br /> After the Liberation of Bulgaria from the Ottoman rule in 1877&ndash;1878, the Turks left to be replaced by Bulgarians from the Balkan Mountains and the villages of the Danube Plain. After the liberation <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> developed as a market town focusing on craftsmanship and agricultural trade. <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> acquired town status in 1943 primarily due to its position on the Sofia-Varna railway line and today the journey takes around 3 and a half hours to Sofia. As of December 2010, the town had a population of 11,604 inhabitants. <br /><br /> Interestingly, <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> Point on Greenwich Island, South Shetland Islands is named after <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> town in Bulgaria and this point juts out into the English Strait in the Antarctic. Furthermore it features in the recent book <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> Point by the Bulgarian writer Dimitar Tomov in 2008. <br /><br /> The Hemus Highway is planned to pass by <strong>Pavlikeni</strong>, connecting the capital city of Sofia with the Black Sea city and port of Varna on the Bulgarian Coastline. <br /><br /> The reconstruction of the central square \"Freedom\" in <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> was an idea to improve the town\'s identity as a whole using the European funds available. It is now a comfortable and peaceful rest area for residents and visitors to <strong>Pavlikeni</strong>.  The reconstruction works project was funded under the Programme for Rural Development and totaled 1,799,894 BGN lvs and was started and completed within the 4 month programme of works, during the summer of 2012. The construction of fountains, new paving throughout the square, turfed areas, recreational areas, playgrounds and an irrigation system, along with the illumination being new energy-saving lamps were the constituent project elements. The area of this project is almost 13,000 m2 and the square is transformed into a town centre which many Western European towns would yearn for. <br /><br /> <strong>What to see and do in Pavlikeni</strong><br /><br /> A major tourism location in the town of <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> is the Museum of History it was founded in 1978 and it has been home to the cultural and historical heritage of <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> and the towns and villages in the region.  The Eternal Calendar created after the idea of Father M.Preobrazenski in 1870 is a unique exhibit from the Renaissance period. The visitors of the museum can visit the Historical Ceramics Centre, a large architectural complex 5 km west from <strong>Pavlikeni</strong>. It originated on an ancient Thracian settlement and it has accommodation of different sizes and functions that are arranged around the inner courtyard with colonnades. There are also the heating channels, Roman bath, preserved and exhibited glaze-kilns and workshops for the production of ceramic utensils for daily life, building materials, and artistic ceramics. A vast array of artifacts including bronze goods, rings, and bracelets, ceramic lamps, terracotta and children\'s toys have been found in the complex. <br /><br /> Also the Art Gallery often has interesting local exhibitions of craft. The art gallery has 2 floors, the 1st for paintings, sketches, local crafts and photography whilst the 2nd floor has a permanent exhibition of \"Archaeology\" antique ceramics (2nd-4th centuries B. C.) \"Renaissance\" the period of the National liberation from the Ottoman, \"Ethnography\" an exhibition of every-day life and labour activity of the residents of the municipality of <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> during the Renaissance period including exhibits used in agriculture and stock-breeding as well as other craftwork including weaving and the ceramic industry. You can also learn about characteristics of the regional traditions including costumes, textiles and embroidery, house furniture, and the holiday rites such as Easter, Weddings and the holiday Trifon Zarezan or St Tryphons Day. \"Modern History\" this section exhibits the development of <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> after 1878. <br /><br /> Also try exploring <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> Zoo. Don\'t expect a London Zoo or San Diego Zoo but this little garden zoo is alive and well and its inhabitants are almost all indigenous to Bulgaria, all be it that your best chance of seeing them alive will likely be in <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> zoo!. Bulgarian zoos don&rsquo;t have the best reputation in the world; however, you will likely be very pleasantly surprised! To find the zoo, enter <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> from Mihaltsi and drive under the railway bridge, when you get to the traffic lights turn right and then drive along the road for approximately 1/2 a kilometre, the zoo is on the right set back and there is some parking in the woods. <br /><br /> <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> Zoo Park has free admission which in this day and age is incredible. When entering you are greeted by domestic chickens, pheasants and rabbits which enthrall children accompanying you. The animals are clean, well-cared for and look healthy showing this by breeding. The zoo offers an opportunity to see some of the wildlife that is usually only seen through a hunter&rsquo;s sight on a rifle! Wild boar, goats and deer have large enclosures and are breeding! Once you walk past the domestic animals, the indigenous animals become more magnificent including beautiful wolves and the highlight being undoubtedly the bears. A mating pair is housed in a very large bear pit, with trees, logs and water, plus good indoor accommodation. <br /><br /> Why not visit on a Tuesday, after shopping down the sprawling and diverse street market which attracts shoppers from all over the region on a Tuesday. The town has a good range of coffee shops and some excellent restaurants where you can eat and drink for a fraction of what you would pay 4 hours away down the railway line in Sofia! <br /><br /> <strong>Alternative spelling for Pavlikeni:</strong> Pavlikeny, Pavlikenny, Pavlickeni, Pavlickenny, Павликени<br /><br /> Nearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo &ndash; 35km, Suhindol &ndash; 12k<br /> Nearest Villages: Mihaltsi - 6km Byala Cherkva - 2.5km<br /> Area size of town 42.221km2<br /> Altitude 100 - 199m above sea level<br /> Post code for <strong>Pavlikeni</strong> Town - 5200<br /> Latitude 43.243N Longitude 25.322E<br /> <span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Pavlikeni</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Pavlikeni - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-pavlikeni/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(146, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-polski-trambesh', 'Property For Sale in Polski Trambesh, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'polski trambesh property for sale, buy properties in polski trambesh', 'Property For Sale in Polski Trambesh Municipality of Veliko Tarnovo - Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in the Municipality of Polski Trambesh', '<p>Polski Trambesh, north of VT, is the administrative centre of Polski Trambesh Municipality</p><h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\"><br />Polski Trambesh is locally renowned for its mineral waters with curative powers which composition challenges the famous Vichy Massif Central in France and the Karlovy Vary in the Czech Republic!<br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Villages in the municipality are:</strong> <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-ivancha/page-1\">Ivancha</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-karantsi/page-1\">Karantsi</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-klimentovo/page-1\">Klimentovo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-kutsina/page-1\">Kutsina</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-maslarevo/page-1\">Maslarevo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-obedinenie/page-1\">Obedinenie</a>, Orlovets, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-pavel/page-1\">Pavel</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-petko-karavelovo/page-1\">Petko Karavelovo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-polski-senovets/page-1\">Polski Senovets</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-radanovo/page-1\">Radanovo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-stefan-stambolovo/page-1\">Stefan Stambolovo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-strahilovo/page-1\">Strahilovo</a>, Varzulitsa<br/><span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Polski Trambesh Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\">\r\nThe town is located very close to the Yantra River, in the central Danube Plain. <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong> translates to \"Trambesh of the fields\", as opposed to Gorski Goren Trambesh \"Upper Trambesh of the forests\" and Gorski Dolen Trambesh \"lower Trambesh of the forests\".  It is unclear whether <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong> developed as a settlement pre-Ottoman times but in 1865 it was a small settlement of 40-50 properties whose population consisted of Bulgarians and Turks. The early construction of the Ruse-Gorna Oryahovitsa rail line ensued its further development when the route opened in 1917 and the village developed into a trading centre with industry establishing after World War I. <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong> was declared a town in 1964. <br/><br/>\r\nNowadays cable TV, covers the whole territory of the town of <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong> and in the western part of the town drilling into the ground has created a spa resort  with a Summer pool and other facilities covering an area of 2872 sqm. <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>What to do in Polski Trambesh:</strong><br/>\r\nThe local Mineral water is an invaluable source of health and in May 1970 drilling led to the discovery of the hyper-thermal aquifer starting at 750 metres to a depth of 1515 m, the water is discharged to the surface from a 2nd \"reservoir\" at around 25 metres deep and the temperature is between 44-47 °C. The flow of the thermal mineral water is 50 to 60 liters per second, wheras in the famous Hissar and Kyustendil the flow rate is only 43 litres per second put together! The \"Louis Pasteur\" centre for medicinal treatments in France recognises that mineral water in France possesses valuable medicinal properties for many different human ailments and analysis has shown varied mineral constituents in the <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong> water comparable and in some cases favouravbly exceeding these recognised quantities of bromine, potassium, sodium, calcium, chloride, magnesium, iron, manganese, lithium, barium, strontium and traces of others. The alkaline nature of the water (pH 7, 7) has a highly prestigious curative and prophylactic effect against the widest variations of human sickness and degeneration such as exhaustion. These include but not solely limited to diseases of the musculoskeletal system, the andrology, gynecology and urology systems, diseases of nervous metabolism, chronic gastritis, colitis, gastrointestinal diseases, ulcers of the stomach and duodenum, various forms of rheumatism, arthritis and cronic arthrosis, diabetes, chronic liver desease, primary biliary cirrhosis and forms of eczema as well as  strengthening the immune system and more. The pool with mineral water is 12.5 m wide, 25 m long and with a depth of between 1.6 m - 2.4 m. It was repaired and re-opened in June 2007 along with fully renovated bathrooms and showers, toilets and changing rooms. The site has a fully functional health centre and sells soft drinks open between 10-00am until 7-00pm. <br/><br/>\r\nIf you fancy something with a bit more action then try the Hunting and Shooting complex. Built in 1984, the complex is located within the area of the \"Hunting Park\" in <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong>, there are indoor and outdoor shooting facilities including clay pigeons, a hunting and administrative building complex with a hotel, conference centre, restaurant and bar. It has hosted international tournaments and Republic of Bulgaria national shooting competitions. <br/><br/>\r\nCulturally, try asking for directions to the old school building, and you will discover a very interesting museum challenging all others in Bulgaria. One of its most emotional exhibits is a human skeleton discovered in a foetal position which is displayed in the centre of one of the old school rooms and was found during excavations near the village of Orlovets in 1993 and scientists have dated the individual to have died some 9000 years ago! In fact this old school house is alive with re-constructed faces and statues, pottery, jewelry and such like dating back from the 4th century BC. A young Thracian woman was buried nearby with her gold jewellery in 400 BC and interestingly they have all been found in the surrounding villages of the municipality of <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong>. Outside the old school lie tombstones of Roman noblemen who lived in the surrounding region some seventeen centuries ago and faces of some of these dead men can be seen carved on these stone tablets of remembrance. You can witness the Bulgarian aristocrat Mostich (showing the last traits of Asian facial features in a Bulgarian), who died in Preslav in the 10th Century AD, as well as Samuil, King of Bulgaria. All these statues of head reconstruction are scientific works of art based on the science of anthropological analysis of skulls, still used in severe homicide cases today, and were put together by the deceased professor Yordan Yordanov, born in <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong> and was the leading \"maestro\" in this scientific art. <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Alternative spellings of Polski Trambesh:</strong> Polski Trumbesh, Polsci Trambesh, Polisci Trumbesh, Polski Trunbesh, Polski Tranbesh, Polski Trambes, Полски Тръмбешo<br/><br/>\r\nNearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo – 36km, Byala – 22km, Gorna Oryahovitsa - 33km<br/>\r\nNearest Villages: Klimentovo - 2.5km, Radanovo - 4km<br/>\r\nArea size of Town of Polski Trambesh: 17.172km2<br/>\r\nLatitude: 43.384N Longitude: 25.65E<br/>\r\nAltitude: 50 - 99m above sea level<br/>\r\nPost code of Town of Polski Trambesh: 5180<br/>\r\n<span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Polski Trambesh</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Polski Trambesh - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-polski-trambesh/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(147, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-strazhitsa', 'Property For Sale in Strazhitsa, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'strazhitsa property for sale, buy properties in strazhitsa', 'Property For Sale in the Municipality of Strazhitsa, Veliko Tarnovo - Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in Strazhitsa Municipality - Veliko Tarnovo Region', '<p>Strazhitsa is the municipality town and centre of the Strazhitsa municipality. Find all the latest properties for sale in Strazhitsa</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\">Strazhitsa is a modern town with many modern buildings after some major redevelopment and has a popular market every Tuesday. Close to the town is the largest lake in the municipality, Kazaldere with a volume of 8 million cubic meters of water!<br/><br/> The town benefits from having a railway station located on the Sofia-Varna rail link only 27km from the railway hub in Gorna Oryahovitsa. <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Villages in the municipality of Strazhitsa: </strong>Asenovo, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-balkantsi/page-1\">Balkantsi</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-blagoevo/page-1\">Blagoevo</a>, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-bryagovitsa/page-1\">Bryagovitsa</a>, Gorski Senovets, Jelezartsi, Kavlak, Kamen, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-kesarevo/page-1\">Kesarevo</a>, Lozen, Lyubentsi,  Mirovo,  <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-nikolaevo/page-1\">Nikolaevo</a>, Nova Varbovka, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-novo-gradishte/page-1\">Novo gradishte</a>, Sushitsa, Temenuga, Tsarski izvor (Chapaevo), Vinograd, <a href=\"en/fast-search-results/latest-property-vladislav/page-1\">Vladislav</a>, Vodno<br/><span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Strazhitsa</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Strazhitsa Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\">\r\n<strong>What to do in Strazhitsa?</strong>\r\nEvery Tuesday there is a market and it has a centre where bills can be paid and weekly shopping carried out. The surrounding countrside of <strong>Strazhitsa</strong> offers rolling hills, good walking, fishing and hunting. <br/><br/>\r\nAugust 15th is the day of Strajitza and on this date marks the celebration of the \"Assumption\". This new church was consecrated on 25. 10. 2007 and is built on the site of the old ruined church \"Nativity of the Virgin Mary,\" which was a cultural revival period building, and the new church bears the same name. In the courtyard of the church is an Orthodox chapel \"St. George\", erected in 2011 in memory of the Russian soldiers who died near <strong>Strazhitsa</strong> in 1877. On August 15th the town has street parties and there are stalls and fairs and local music, song and dance. <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Strazhitsa</strong> has a Gallery housing a rich collection of 786 paintings and drawings and 93 sculptures. The gallery is in the exhibition hall along with a museum exhibition collection demonstrating the development of <strong>Strazhitsa</strong> from the Thracian times to the present day. <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Alternative spellings of Strazhitsa: </strong> Strazitsa, Strajica, Strazitsa, Strajitsa, Strazhica, Strazica, Strazhitza, Стражица<br/><br/>\r\nNearest Towns: Zlataritsa – 27km, Gorna Oryahovitsa – 30km, Veliko Tarnovo - 38km<br/>\r\nNearest Villages: Mirovo - 8km,  Vladislav - 8km, Chapaevo (Tsarski izvor) – 7km<br/>\r\nArea size of Town of <strong>Strazhitsa</strong>: 50.073km2<br/>\r\nAltitude: 50 - 99m above sea level<br/>\r\nPost code of Town of <strong>Strazhitsa</strong>: 5150<br/>\r\nLatitude: 43.2333N Longitude: 25.9667E<br/>\r\n\r\n<span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Strazhitsa</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Strazhitsa - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-strazhitsa/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(148, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-suhindol', 'Property For Sale in Suhindol, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'suhindol property for sale, buy properties in suhindol', 'Property For Sale in Suhindol Municipality of Veliko Tarnovo - Bulgaria', 'Latest property for sale in the Suhindol Municipality of Veliko Tarnovo', '<p>The town of Suhindol is located in North-Central Bulgaria and is the municipality town for <strong>Suhindol</strong> Municipality.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\"><strong>Suhindol</strong> is a big vine growing and wine producing centre. It was as early as 1897 when its population imported grapevines from France and developed vine sprinklers.<span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Suhindol</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Suhindol Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"><strong>Villages in the municipality of Suhindol</strong>: Byala Reka, Gorsko Kalugerovo, Gorsko Kosovo, Koevtsi, Krasno Gradishte<br /><br /><strong>Suhindol</strong> became a big cultural centre in its heyday, after the Ottoman Empire was pushed out of this region. The community centre dates back to 1870 and the very distinctive clock tower dates back to 1895 and is a local landmark that can be seen for miles. <br /><br /><strong>Suhindol</strong> is located on the North Route of the Bulgarian Wine Trail and one particular winery, Lovico, has a fascinating wine museum which exhibits the company\'s wine making history and viticulture traditions throughout its life and of the surrounding <strong>Suhindol</strong> region. We strongly would recommend you to try out tastings here since they have been doing them for decades, arguably the pioneers of wine tourism! After tastings there is a museum and an art gallery in the town. The painting \"<strong>Suhindol</strong> Maiden\" painted by Felix Kanits in 1872 is exhibited in the art gallery amongst other works of art. <br /><br />Lovico <strong>Suhindol</strong> winery is the direct successor to the oldest vine-growing and winemaking cooperative on the Balkans, in 1908 the first independent vine-growing and wine-producing co-operative company in Bulgaria was established - Gumza. Nowadays the annual production capacity is in excess of 5 million litres and approximately 50 per cent of this production is exported. If you measured the total length of all the rows of vineyards just at Lovico winery it would be equal to the distance by road from <strong>Suhindol</strong> to Venice, 1353 km! <br /><br /><strong>Specific wines worth tasting!</strong><br /><br /> <strong>Cabernet Sauvignon</strong> is always good from Lovico <strong>Suhindol</strong>, however if you can lay your hands upon and taste a 2007 vintage, please enjoy! It is an elegant, fruity and yet complex wine, hidden notes of blackcurrants and redcurrant fruit, explode in a symphony of tannins and tongue teasing delight! <br /><br />The local Gumza red wine, especially from 2006, 2007 and 2008 is a cherry hinted deep red with scents of mint and vanilla, serve around 15-18 degs C with white cheese, but remember to soak the cheese in water to get excess salt out! <br /><br />And last but by no means least look out for a 2008 Lovico Chardonnay, vinted from carefully selected ripe grapes, this wine displays aromas of grapefruit and a fresh taste of peaches. The overtones of oak pleasantly complement the light fruity attributes of Chardonnay grapes whilst eating artichokes cold meats, olives and light cheeses such as a mild kashkaval. <br /><br /> Alternative Spellings of <strong>Suhindol:</strong> Sukindol, Suckindol, Suhindal, Sukindal, Сухиндол<br /><br /> Nearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo &ndash; 50km, Pavlikeni &ndash; 12k<br /> Nearest Villages: Dimcha - 5km Gorsko Kosovo - 11km<br /> Area size of town 65.798km2<br /> Altitude 200 - 299m above sea level<br /> Post code for Suhindol Town - 5240<br /> <span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Suhindol</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Suhindol - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-suhindol/page-1', 'Desktop'),
(149, 'en', 'fast-search-results', 'latest-property-svishtov', 'Property For Sale in Svishtov, Bulgaria | Yantra Homes', 'svishtov property for sale, buy properties in svishtov', 'Property For Sale in Svishtov Municipality of Veliko Tarnovo - Bulgaria', 'Property For Sale in the Municipality of Svishtov - Veliko Tarnovo Region', '<p>The very latest property for sale in the municipality of Svishtov - Veliko Tarnovo region of North Bulgaria.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0;\">Svishtov is situated at the southernmost point of the Danube, the terrain being slightly hilly and flatlands adjacent to the river it was also the 1st Bulgarian town to be liberated from the Ottoman rule in June 1877. <span id=\"link_view\" class=\"clear_l pointer f_right mt_5px\" style=\"display: block;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_hide\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Read more about <strong>Svishtov</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_down.png\" alt=\"Veliko Tarnovo Property &ndash; Read More\" /> </span></h3>\r\n<div id=\"text_more\" class=\"clear_l mt_10px display_none fs_13px a_justify \" style=\"width: 672px; color: #4a4a4a; display: none;\"><strong>Villages in the municipality of Svishtov</strong>:  Alekovo, Aleksandrovo, Bulgarsko Slivovo, Chervena, Gorna Studena, Delyanovtsi, Dragomirovo, Hadjidimitrovo, Kozlovets, Morava, Oresh, Ovcha mogila, Sovata, Tsarevets, Vardim.<br/><br/>\r\nThe Danube town was originally a Roman naval town called Nove (1st century) and due to its location was a strategically important trading centre with naval functions since the Danube was a water highway to the Black Sea, as it still is today. On the map of Fra Maura, which is considered one of the best examples of medieval cartography and drawn around 1450 by the Italian monk of the same name, Fra Mauro. It is a detailed planisphere drawn on linen and set in an ornate wooden frame 2 metres in diameter and <strong>Svishtov</strong> is named as Sistovo. In 1651 the first book written in the new Bulgarian language was created in <strong>Svishtov</strong>.  Svesht, meaning candle, is where the current name originates from, during the Ottoman Rule the small town lit fires along the banks of the Danube allowing boats to safely navigate this stretch of the river at night. Over time the town of <strong>Svishtov</strong> expanded and the town attained mass development during the 19th century despite its destruction during the Russian-Turkish War of 1810. By 1870 nearly a thousand stores were open for business and over seven hundred warehouses were built to support these stores. A high school of economics was established in <strong>Svishtov</strong> in 1873, which was the 1st such school in Bulgaria. Felix Kanits the 19th Century geographer often called \"The Balkan Columbus” wrote, \"<strong>Svishtov</strong> has been enjoying the reputation of a European town with a European market for a long time.\" Shipping developed at a fast pace with a steam shipping company being based in <strong>Svishtov</strong>, towing huge barges carrying cereals and other agricultural produce. <br/><br/>\r\nThe wealth and welfare of the town folk is reflected in its cultural life, Hristaki Pavlovich established a new Bulgarian school and a secular school for girls. One of the first chitalishta (reading-clubs) in Bulgaria with a museum with it was built in <strong>Svishtov</strong> in 1856, thanks to Elenka and Kiril Avramovi donating part of their wealth. In 1833 the first Bulgarian mathematics textbook was written and in 1836 the first Bulgarian geometry textbook was written. In 1884, the first in Bulgaria Commercial High School opened its gates (today\'s High School of Economy). Bulgarian Revival notable people including Emanuil Vaskidovich, Nikolai Pavlovich and Hristaki Pavlovich based themselves in <strong>Svishtov</strong>. <br/><br/>\r\nIn June 1877 the specialist platoons of the Russian Army crossed the Danube River in the locality of the village of Vardim only 3km from <strong>Svishtov</strong> which commenced the Russian-Turkish War of Liberation. The occupying Turks put up a ferocious defence during this 1st battle and 814 members of the Russian army lost their lives. After the Liberation, <strong>Svishtov</strong> remained an important economic and cultural centre, whilst Ruse grew as a commercial centre. Since 1936 <strong>Svishtov</strong> gained its title as an academic town, after the opening of the Dimitar Tsenov Academy of Economics, which now has 4 faculties: Faculty of Economic Accounting;  Faculty of Management and Marketing; Faculty of Production and Commercial Business; School of Finance. When Dimitar Apostolov Tsenov died he left 50 million Bulgarian leva for the construction and operation of a European based academy in <strong>Svishtov</strong> - this is now the Tsenov Academy of economics. <br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Svishtov</strong> is the birthplace of Tsvetan Radoslavov famous for writing the song, Mila Rodino (Dear Motherland) which the Bulgarian national anthem music was composed around and birthplace of the famed and revered Bulgarian writer, Patron of the Bulgarian hiking movement, humorist and democrat Aleko Konstantinov. One of his books, \"To Chicago and Back\" consisted of his intriguing travel notes from his American trip, which initiated an interest in the USA and specifically Chicago which draws the largest concentration of Bulgarians emigrating to the US, furthermore in keeping with <strong>Svishtov</strong>\'s academic history, the writer is honoured with a bust of Aleko in the Regenstein Library, Chicago University. <br/><br/>\r\n\r\n\r\n<strong>What to do in Svishtov?</strong><br/><br/>\r\n<strong>Svishtov</strong> has in excess of 120 architectural monuments, buildings and artifacts of local and national significance. Museums consist of the Museum of History being the oldest museum in Bulgaria, dating back to 1856, the Aleko Konstantinov House-Museum (his heart being pickled in a glass container), the Ethnographic Museum, the Holy Trinity Church built in 1867, another great example of the Bulgarian master builder and architect of the Revival period Kolyo Ficheto and decorated internally by Nikolai Pavlovich\'s icons, who lived in <strong>Svishtov</strong>. The church was damaged during the earthquake of 1977; however it was lovingly restored by 1992. Also worth visiting are the medieval St. Dimiter Church (1640) and St. Peter and Pavel Church (1644). The clock tower built in 1760 in the centre of <strong>Svishtov</strong> is a landmark. Look for the School of Hristaki Pavlovich built in 1815 and the House of Peace, which gets its name from the Austrian-Turkish separation peace treaty signed in 1729. The beautiful old Revival houses of Sladkarov, Danailov, Hrulev, Bruchkov, Cherkezov, Radoslavov and the house of the Subevs Brothers are all worth checking out as well. <br/><br/>\r\nTake a 3km journey east to Pametnitsite Historical Park which commemorates the Russian soldiers who died while liberating <strong>Svishtov</strong> in the Russo-Turkish War. There are granite and white marble statues and lovely parklands along with a small museum about the historical events which changed the future of Bulgaria. The remains of the ancient town of Nove dating back to the first century AD and the medieval town of Stuklen are found nearby, being forerunners of the modern day <strong>Svishtov</strong> town. Pisanite Kamuni, meaning the inscribed stones is an area 2 km east of <strong>Svishtov</strong> and here you can find artifacts and tools from the early Paleolithic time. <br/><br/>\r\nThe island of Vardim, an ornithologist’s delight, is sited about 10 km east of <strong>Svishtov</strong> in the river Danube and after Belene and Kozlodui is the 3rd largest Bulgarian island on the Danube. It is now a nature reserve thanks to colonies of birds nesting there including birds dependent on riverside forest habitats. It supports 75 bird species, 31 of which are of European conservation concern.  The international importance of Vardim Island is determined by the fact, that it is one of the five most valuable Bulgarian sites for the breeding Night Heron and Spoonbill that form considerable colonies there and the White-tailed Eagle is breeding once again on the island. <br/><br/>\r\n20 km further east its worth going to see a white stone monument in the Yaakov Gurlo area, close to the intersection of the river Yantra with the Danube, which commemorates the 18th June 1868 when a detachment of armed volunteers of Harzhi Dimiter and Stefan Karadzha disembarked from the sailing boat Gemiya onto their native riverbank, thereby making further Bulgarian history. Further afield, 30km south, at Gorna Studena its worth visiting the Headquarters of the Russian Emperor, but check the opening times 1st! <br/><br/>\r\n\r\n<strong>Alternative spellings of Svishtov:</strong>  Zvishtov, Tsvishtov, Svishtof, Свищов<br/><br/>\r\nNearest Towns: Veliko Tarnovo – 82km, Ruse – 83km, Polski Trambesh - 45km<br/>\r\nNearest Villages: Vardim - 9km Tsarevets - 7km<br/>\r\nArea size of town 110.271km2<br/>\r\nAltitude 50 - 99m above sea level<br/>\r\nPost code for <strong>Svishtov</strong> Town - 5250<br/>\r\nLatitude: 43.62042N Longitude: 25.34632E<br/>\r\n\r\n<span id=\"link_hide\" class=\"clear_l pointer mt_5px f_right display_none\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"$(\'div#text_more\').slideToggle(); $(this).hide(); $(\'span#link_view\').show();\"> <span class=\"link\">Hide information about <strong>Svishtov</strong></span> <img style=\"display: inline; float: none; width: 8px;\" src=\"application/images/arrow_up.png\" alt=\"Property in Lyaskovets - Hide\" /> </span></div>', 'www.yantrahomes.co.uk/en/fast-search-results/latest-property-svishtov/page-1', 'Desktop');
